rs' belief in American distrust and disunity. Neither of these myths, however, will adequately curb political violence. Williams suggests that the amendment should serve not as a rule of law but as a cultural ideal that promotes our unity on the use of political violence and celebrates our diversity in other areas of life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aArmes à feuxDroitxHistoirexÉtats-Unis. 0aFirearmsxLaw and legislationxHistoryxUnited States. 0aFirearmsxLaw and legislationzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aGovernment, Resistance toxHistoryxUnited States. 0aGovernment, Resistance tozUnited StatesxHistory. 0aPolitical violencexHistoryxUnited States. 0aPolitical violencezUnited StatesxHistory. 0aRésistance au gouvernementxHistoirexÉtats-Unis. 0aViolence politiquexHistoirexÉtats-Unis. 7aLAW / Constitutional.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066772108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013z978311053799440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300127553423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300127553.jpg  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066772-1  YUP eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles